                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d756">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890E.01/123: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Consul General at Beirut</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Engert</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-02-20T23:00:00-04:00"
                            >February 20, 1942—11 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>25. Your no. 11, January 16, and no. 35, February 6, 9 p.m. The question of the
                    recognition of Syrian and Lebanese independence continues to receive the
                    Department’s very active consideration, and although there are certain
                    inter-related problems which complicate the question, a further instruction to
                    you should be possible in the near future.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Welles</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
